But I am. I am really really attracted to them. And I don't know what the hell to do with that. I don't know how to give my trust, my love, or my body to a man. Or if it's even a good idea to. And that is so incredibly frustrating. But I know I'm done being ashamed of it.

It is so easy as a bisexual woman to just pretend I'm not attracted to them. The nonbinary people and women in my life are all so incredibly wonderful. And the men I've let into my life just hurt me. Why would I ever want to be attracted to them?

How the fuck do I not just be pissed?? At patriarchy, at biphobia, and at men as a whole. How do I suck a man's cock without getting pissed off? How do I love a man without fearing him? Without hating him for having the fucking gal to love me?

And not just the fear, this internalized misogyny I know lurks in me. The one patriarchy left me and the one biphobic lesbians projected on to me. The feeling my very own kinks love to indulge in a fucked fetishization of cisgender men. This inferiority I feel as a woman.

I can acknowledge the biphobia as just that. Fuck the all too common bisexual sentiment that it's a curse to be attracted to men. Fuck the lesbians who would happily erase that attraction. But at the same time, how on earth can I reconcile that with this now deep rooted fear?

And now I'm realizing that shame. That repressed heterosexuality that lies in my bisexuality. And removing a bit of shame all that's there is frustration and mourning and frustration that I'm still fucking mourning. And just. Confusion. What the fuck do I do now?

My rapist left me ashamed of my attraction to men. The feminism I adopted left me ashamed of it. Biphobia I got from lesbians (and other bisexuals) left me ashamed of it. It was disgusting and immoral and I got hurt because of it. It was right to be ashamed. And I still am.

A lot of people told me that it was good I wasn't attracted to men. That I'd finally gotten past that horrible curse. And I agreed. I was free from my abusers, who had left me warry of all men. But in truth that "freedom" was actually just shame I created.

Before my rape, I liked to say things like I was cursed to be attracted to men. After my rape I took up the mantle of a lesbian. Decided my attraction to men was just comp het. And even when I did come back to bisexuality, I was decidedly attracted to everyone BUT men.

The thing is, I LOVE men. Their smell. Big muscles. Rough skin. Deep harsh voices. Bluntness and abrasiveness. All the things stereotypically masculine. I love them. And they're also all the traits my two biggest abusers had.

TW /// rape

I hate how much I've had to downplay my attraction to men out of legitimate shame for it. And I hate that it's so much more complicated than just biphobia. How do I handle my attraction to men in the face of patriarchy, biphobia, hetero culture, and my own rape.

❤️weird vent thread from Sofia. Being a bisexual woman is so fucking difficult to navigate. Especially heterosexual attraction. It's all so frustrating. Biphobia from lesbians makes me so incredibly angry and at the same time it can be so hard not to perpetuate it as a bisexual.

Rothko pushed the boundaries of what art can be and in so doing so elicited the emotion of thousands if not millions, my self included. At the very least I ask you do not judge these paintings until you are able to see them in person. No screen will ever do them justice.

If you gain nothing or feel nothing from a Rothko painting, that is fine. Art is, after all, subjective. You don't have to like Rothko. But don't think of others who do as pretentious or faking it when they do feel emotion due to these fields of color.

Rothko did with his paintings is marvelous. Many believe that art is for the sake of impression. That art should be a display of skill. Or that there is some secret meaning to be found. When the truth is art is just pretty colors. Rothko shows this more than any other.

The beauty of non-objective art is that it is in and of itself beautiful without the reliance on reality. They are able to reduce beauty to their bare essentials. And in so doing they create a space for the viewer to make their own.

People underestimate how encapsulating these painting can be. While they may be mere colors, there's so much more to explore in the paint. And there's so much emotion that can be found in them if you're willing to look. These paintings have made me cry.

There is literally nothing more to Rothko paintings than that they are big big color. You cannot judge a Rothko painting based on a jpeg posted on twitter. We are gender, sexual, and romantic minorities. All of us are oppressed by cis hetero society. The xenogender is my ally. The asexual and the aromantic is my ally. The person who has trouble sticking to an identity is my ally. And I'll stand in solidarity with all of them.

But the caste needs to be destroyed within GSRM communities While we are subjected to what cishet society creates for us, we are all minorities, and we are all ultimately viewed as near equally abominable. I do not want to grovel and claim that i'm one of the good queers.

I believe that we all do want to be higher on that social caste. To be as acceptable as cis white gay men are seen. And it's that emotion that's kept me from identifying as a lesbian. As a nb person. As a genderfluid person.

As someone who has been viciously told that I am not queer, that I do not belong within GSRM circles, my immediate instinct is to stand with anyone who's experience what I have experienced. And I've also felt that temptation to expel those who I'd deem as less acceptable than me.

This is why I am extremely wary of any attempts at gatekeeping within our community. While there are exceptions (i.e. pedos), discourse around identities such as xenogenders, bi lesbians, or ace/aro folk often reeks of that same appeal to cishet society from truscum or biphobes.

But in truth this caste is not as extreme from the cishet perspective. From the gatekeeper's view, a gay man is much more acceptable than a trans lesbian. However, a cishet is generally unable to distinguish between a drag queen and a trans women.

And the arguments are often that the inclusion of those on the lower caste is at the detriment of those above them. The binary trans woman will claim she would have it easier if trans people held to the cis binary. The lesbian can't get rights if a trans lesbian exists.

Biphobic gate keeping from lesbians and gays. Trans gatekeeping from LGB. NB gatekeeping from truscum tans folk. Ace/aro gatekeeping from all of us. We want to decide who belongs and who doesn't, and we target those lower on the caste than us for but the sake of cishets.

I believe that many of us do want to have a leg up on the pile. To be seen as "not as bad" as other GSRM identities which have yet to be accepted by cishet society. The most plain examples of this to me are both truscum and wlw TERFS. But I this behavior manifests in many ways

More on gate keeping in queer circles: GSRM folks have in a way been forced to but also employ a sort of caste system wherein some of us are seen as more acceptable or hold more power than others. While it's important to note that none of us have the power and comfort of cishets-
